  "text": "Firefox initiates a TLS connection through the following chain:\n\n1. **HTTP Protocol Layer** (netwerk/protocol/http/nsHttpConnection.cpp): The `nsHttpConnection` class manages HTTP connections and initiates TLS setup for HTTPS connections by creating a TLSTransportLayer.\n\n2. **TLS Transport Layer** (netwerk/protocol/http/TLSTransportLayer.cpp): The TLSTransportLayer bridges the HTTP protocol layer to the SSL socket provider, handling the transformation of raw sockets into TLS-encrypted connections.\n\n3. **SSL Socket Provider** (security/manager/ssl/nsSSLSocketProvider.cpp): The `nsSSLSocketProvider::NewSocket()` method creates a new SSL socket by calling `nsSSLIOLayerNewSocket()` from the NSS I/O layer integration.\n\n4. **NSS I/O Layer Helpers** (security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.h): The `nsSSLIOLayerHelpers` class manages TLS configuration, version negotiation, and intolerance handling. It bridges Necko (Firefox's network library) to NSS (Network Security Services).\n\n5. **NSS I/O Layer Integration** (security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.cpp): The `nsSSLIOLayerNewSocket()` function creates an SSL socket and `nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket()` adds SSL/TLS capabilities to an existing socket. The key function `nsSSLIOLayerImportFD()` at line 1269 calls `SSL_ImportFD(nullptr, fd)` to import the file descriptor into NSS, which initializes the SSL context and binds callbacks for handshake, authentication, and certificate verification.\n\n6. **NSS Handshake Orchestration** (security/nss/lib/ssl/sslsecur.c): The `ssl_Do1stHandshake()` function at line 33 orchestrates the TLS handshake by calling version-specific handshake handlers. The `ssl_FinishHandshake()` function at line 54 finalizes the handshake after successful protocol negotiation.\n\n7. **Protocol-Specific Handshake** (security/nss/lib/ssl/ssl3con.c and tls13con.c): The `ssl3con.c` file implements the TLS 1.2 and earlier handshake protocols, while `tls13con.c` implements the TLS 1.3 handshake. These files contain the actual cryptographic protocol implementation including ClientHello/ServerHello exchange, key derivation, certificate exchange, and finished message verification."
}

